               <note>
                  <date type="foundation" notBefore="1400" notAfter="1500">1400-1500</date>
                  <desc type="foundation">The church may be an Aksumite foundation. Aksumite remains (a massive stone bowl, pillar) are found in the church compound. 
                     Local tradition does not specify the time of the foundation, but tells that <persName ref="PRS10340Yeshaq">Yǝsḥaq</persName>, the founder of <placeName ref="INS0005Gund">Gunda Gunde</placeName> and adherent of the Stephanite movement, 
                     established the monastic community at the church of Nǝḥbi before going to the area where he founded later <placeName ref="INS0005Gund">Gunda Gunde</placeName> (The <ref type="work" corresp="LIT4810GadlaYe">Vita of Yǝsḥaq</ref> tells 
                     only that he was a native of Nǝḥba in ʿAgāma). 
                     As other churches and monasteries of the area, the monastic community of 
                     Nǝḥbi was favored by <persName ref="PRS8265Sabagadi">Dağğāzmāč Sabāgādis</persName>, in the early 19th cent., but it declined in the early 20th cent.  
                     During the Italian period another church dedicated to <persName ref="PRS10618ZaraB" type="tabot">Zarʾā Buruk</persName> was established nearby under the administration of Nǝḥbi Mikāʾel, but it declined in the early 20th cent.</desc>
                  <ab type="history">Gadām. It is considered a monastery, but currently there are no monks.&#xD;
</ab>
                  <ab type="description">
